height: 1.16em; margin: 1em 0 0.625em 0;"><strong>How Ethereum Makes Money<=
/strong></h3><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px=
; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">I&#8217;ve been aware of Ethereum for a long time. I =
first bought (then sold) ETH in 2017, but it was speculative and I didn&#82=
17;t get it. The big question mark I had with Ethereum was how it made mone=
y. <strong>How does more activity on top of Ethereum translate into a highe=
r price for ETH?</strong></p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; l=
ine-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">In the near future, the answer will b=
e that more transactions mean higher yields for ETH holders and a decreasin=
g supply of ETH. But that&#8217;s not how it works, yet.&nbsp;</p><p style=
=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;"=
>Let&#8217;s start with how it works today, look at the challenges of the c=
urrent model, the proposed solutions, and what it will look like in the fut=
ure.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26p=
x; margin: 0 0 1em 0;"><em>(Note: For a more in-depth explanation, listen t=
o <a href=3D"https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkctq7DAMhp8mXgZfM87Ci0Mvd=
FFoFy09nE3wRZ7xNLGD7bSkT1_PzOKAkISE-H8-WV3hmPKu1lQquqSp7iuoCN9lhloho61AnoJT=
ZKCSCT4ip7gjUkgUyuQzwKLDrGreAK2bmYPVNaR4vcCYCnS6VA_MeGuMIwaod95Iay0TgyZEHm6=
6enMBogUFX5D3FAHN6lTrWjr2p6OPLdIKsS9rqsHvvU1LG8EaSnLQOvHv78_zw_MH4XLUd-f316=
fz2wvv2GMJHbunjjkvDR4PB8_d6FBQFFOCBeWECi5YT3oqoRk01gjLLNOEulFgOhIrhHDW-o7j5=
Uj7splStf28OEBZxVRNyiEe2_rzpBeYr4uGYmp12WKo-wRRmxncjVK9wb5ym44QIbcnuEnXC2Ii=
BzxiLhvnK5WGkQ2DPDA2oqbsUruK_0V_AdpnlVA" style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; text-deco=
ration: underline;">Justin Drake on Business Breakdowns</a>)</em><strong>To=
day</strong></p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 2=
6px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Today, when you want to transact on Ethereum, you =
need to use ETH. There are currently around 116 million ETH, and the price =
is loosely governed by supply and demand. More transactions on Ethereum mea=
ns more demand for ETH which means higher price, all else equal.&nbsp;</p><=
p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 =
1em 0;">When you transact, say if you send another person ETH, a few things=
 happen:&nbsp;</p><ul style=3D"margin: 1em 0;"><li style=3D"margin: 3.75px =
0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;"><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; fo=
nt-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">You send 1 ETH and the other =
person receives 1 ETH</p></li><li style=3D"margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; m=
so-special-format: bullet;"><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; li=
ne-height: 26px; margin: 0;">You pay gas fees, say .01 ETH</p></li><li styl=
e=3D"margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;"><p style=
=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">Your ac=
count balance on the chain goes down by 1.01 ETH, theirs goes up by 1 ETH</=
p></li></ul><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px;=
 margin: 0 0 1em 0;">To keep Ethereum running, it uses a <a href=3D"https:/=
/email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFUtuOnDAM_Rp4Kwq5MPDAQ7vd_YK-o-B4hmhCghLTWf6-I=
Wy1UuRL4vgc2Qc04SPEY9xCovo0Ex0bjh5fySERxnpPGCdrxrbjvVByqM0oTdurvrZpukfEVVs3=
Utyx3vbZWdBkgy8_GOOqXkYQvVQakPEWZxCayeEmGUjkZuhlCxeu3o1FDzjiX4xH8Fi7cSHaUiV=
-VvwjH6QFI-5rE-LjTH02Jle7sGFMZxLgdBB8Qp_29GNFWLS3aT2vt_AqfcTZ8PaeLeEnVeL3-1=
ffiiv-dhrm7BNL8MsSBOu_X2CPET25o2R5NrnzG2AkfVWxp_UmlSjci8NMJ6wWSqKJNDxTU_HuC=
_zPYq_yl3XuqnEplGBbdLpohJ2KX623_lHCewyFMPvPvqntyPOImeKy5Uoq0bQN73GezQyzApEn=
3-aJK8aHFpRSBuBeSbY-eJP2OZ3EGghrHUcfaA7xRJLsuegVXXnI652yX3dv6ZjQ69mhuTZPl4C=
KFqYHeoxZWGbSdMqm7Ts2MNln7ZRNZ2mIrutvQgx1RjYh__LfoP8AWMnW8g" style=3D"color=
: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">Proof of Work consensus mechanism</=
a> to trustlessly agree on the state of the blockchain. Bitcoin also uses P=
roof of Work, that&#8217;s where Ethereum got it from, although Bitcoin min=
ing is able to be run on cheaper hardware and has 20x more miners than Ethe=
reum, and is therefore more decentralized.</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; f=
ont-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">PoW achieves the sam=
e thing as your bank account balance going up and someone else&#8217;s goin=
g down when they send you money, except in the place of a centralized bank,=
 there is a distributed network of miners who agree that these transactions=
 occurred and that all balances are updated.</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a;=
 font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">To do it, miners a=
round the world race to solve increasingly difficult cryptographic problems=
 in order to create a new block on the blockchain containing the new transa=
ctions. These problems are typically hard to solve -- read: require a lot o=
f energy -- but <a href=3D"https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFUc3OpCAQfJr=
hphEQxQOH77KvYfhp1IyCC80a334Z5_AlnabTRacqVVYjLDHd6owZyafNeJ-gAlx5B0RIpGRI8-=
YUHZjkop-IU72jUkiy5dkngENvu8JUgJzF7JvVuMXwXHQdE2RVholR-slb3xsY2aC5HsFZw83kp=
aD0y6uL2yBYUPAP0h0DkF2tiGd-8Z8X-1Pr0LjGCvo9Xm0ArKu_BfKHLteZDdMohzpcq8bGxuMs=
-GjRe3OmaHY4cnPFsrvGQLPE6D7r6JtaV0zv308-psam-8RoS0pANsU6RjvBespEL3hLWybBGGe=
sEZZbrilzk-jYRK0QwlnrX313LKzNxWTU9t1WOSSpENHEtIWlwu9VH7A_QPVtru9Rwob3DEFXGe=
5rKX6TeUyeFwiQamJu1vjJg8qhm7pe1lAeC6vnfBjkyPlEKrOL9Sr8kv4Hvwip7A" style=3D"=
color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">easy to verify</a>. When a blo=
ck is entered into the blockchain, the transactions in it officially become=
 part of the record. Miners who successfully create a block are rewarded wi=
th 2 freshly-minted ETH (down from 5 in the beginning) and all the transact=
ion fees within the block.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: =
16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Those transaction fees, called=
 <strong>gas</strong>, are what people pay to submit transactions to be inc=
luded in the block. When a user sends someone ETH on Ethereum, or mints an =
NFT, or does any number of things that need to be validated on-chain, they =
have to pay a gas fee. That gas fee goes towards incentivizing miners to sp=
end the money required, in the form of hardware and electricity, to solve t=
he puzzle and create the block.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-s=
ize: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">So currently, the price o=
f Ethereum is based on a combination of supply and demand, and the price it=
 costs miners to secure the blockchain. To participate, you need ETH, and y=
ou need to pay the gas. Miners receive ETH in the form of newly-minted supp=
ly and your fees. Miners pay for hardware and electricity and taxes, and ke=
ep ~5% of their earnings. Today, most of the value accrues to GPU makers, e=
lectric utilities, and the government, with the miner&#8217;s portion compe=
ted down to close to 0.</p><div style=3D"font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px=
;"><hr style=3D"background: #e0ecf6; border: none; height: 1px; margin: 24p=
